<TEXT>
alexander dubcek ousted from power by the soviet 
22 years ago in czechoslovakia on monday said lithuanians should 
negotiate their independence with moscow and that neither side 
should provoke the use of force 
dubcek one of three senior officials in the czechoslovak 
government ended a fourday official visit his first since 1968 
with a meeting with president mikhail s gorbachev 
he told a news conference that time and patience were needed to 
resolve the impasse between the kremlin and the breakaway baltic 
republic which declared independence march 11 
dubcek said the lithuanian declaration was something that 
happened in such a way that solution is not possible today but 
will be possible tomorrow 
although every nation has the right to selfdeterminaion he 
said lithuania and the soviet union should look for optimum 
solutions and compromise to settle the issue and arrive at a 
transition period during which emotions die down 
both sides dubcek aid should not lose patience and avoid 
any possible conflict 
as leader of the czechoslovak communist party he led the 
prague spring movement in 1968 and ran afoul of the soviet 
hardliners who ordered warsaw pact forces to invade on aug 21 that 
year 
tass quoted gorbachev as discussing the invasion with dubcek 
that action had a negative effect on the development of the 
soviet union itself led to a freeze of planned reforms and slowed 
down the natural development of progressive processes and pushed 
the country to the blind alleys of stagnation gorbachev said 
</TEXT>
