<DOCNO> AP900522-0007 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
fast food is getting faster with a computerized 
device introduced monday that turns customers into order takers 
isnt rude and like regular clerks even asks if they wouldnt 
like a soda with their fries 
the 8470 computer would give customers more control over 
their orders and increased employee efficiency amid a troubling 
labor shortage said officials at ibm which developed the product 
and a fastfood chain that recently began using it 
if a customer orders a sandwich and salad for example but no 
soft drink the screen illuminates a printed message saying 
would you like a refreshing soda 
as the customer places the order it appears on similar screens 
in the kitchen area eliminating the need for clerks to shout or 
walk orders back to the cooks 
the system is designed for one clerk to handle two terminals for 
two lines of customers 
bilingual versions are also available ibm officials said in 
unveiling the system at the national restaurant associations 
international trade show 
we think its fantastic said mark eagleton vice president 
of a branch of the bailey co which manages about 60 arbys roast 
beef restaurants in five states bailey based in lakewood colo 
is an independent arbys franchisee and has installed eight of the 
devices in its stores 
eagleton said the system has improved service times by about 
20 seconds per order its improved the accuracy of the orders 
its increased our capacity for sales by allowing us to serve more 
customers with the same amount of employees 
and he said customers buy more 
weve seen our average check go up between 9 cents and 40 
cents an order per store he said 
arbys is ibms first client with about 20 restaurants around 
the country using the device eagleton says its being used in 
eight of his arbys and will be installed in all new or remodeled 
arbys managed by his company 
ibm also introduced a notebooksized radiocontrolled order 
board for use by clerks at driveins the clerk intercepts 
customers before they reach the pickup window and punches in the 
order it then appears on a screen in the kitchen and is ready by 
the time the driver arrives at the window 
its being used in about 30 wendys hamburger restaurants 
nationwide but also could be used in sitdown restaurants said ibm 
spokeswoman cindy beck 
the devices come as the industry faces a shrinking work force 
eagleton said 
were having a shortage of workers thoughout the 90s and if 
we can automate more so that whatever workers we do have can be 
used more effectively its going to have a substantial impact 
he said 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP900522-0008 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
from africa to latin america to eastern 
europe moscows domain is crumbling 
soviet troops have left afghanistan the marxist regime in 
nicaragua is history ethiopia and mozambique are veering from 
their rigid prosoviet ideologies 
not to mention the disintegration of the iron curtain 
the speed of it all has taken mikhail s gorbachev by surprise 
and dramatically altered his stance as he heads into next weeks 
washington summit meetings with president bush 
soviet leaders and american presidents have met since nikolai 
bulganin and dwight eisenhower gathered with the leaders of britain 
and france in 1955 10 years after josef stalin won territorial 
concessions at yalta that some said helped tighten the soviet grip 
in eastern europe 
for decades after bulganin and eisenhower met in geneva moscow 
widened its circle of influence becoming to ronald reagan in 
1983 the evil empire 
how quickly things change in less than a year 
poland and hungary have held free elections resoundingly 
defeating candidates who represented the status quo 
czechoslovakias parliament elected dissident playwright 
vaclav havel as president replacing communist gustav husak 
bulgarias head of state todor zhivkov resigned 
nicolae ceausescu was executed in romania 
east germany dissolved its communist government and opened the 
berlin wall it is headed toward reunification with west germany 
within the soviet union gorbachevs power is threatened by 
ethnic and economic nationalists 
he has been jeered by crowds in red square he has been 
criticized within the communist party for being too fast or too 
slow in remaking the soviet political and economic systems he has 
dispatched troops to quell ethnic violence 
he has beseeched lithuania unsuccessfully not to declare 
itself independent he is trying to cajole two other baltic 
republics latvia and estonia not to follow the lithuanians 
gorbachev has applied increasing economic pressure to lithuania 
to rescind its declaration and president bush has said the standoff 
between moscow and the baltic republics certainly puts some 
tension on the summit 
in all gorbachev will go into the summit with less of a power 
base than any of his postwar predecessors 
it puts gorbachev in a weakened position in which he basically 
has to in effect ask the west for its indulgence as he tries to 
ride out the crises said michael j sodaro a george washington 
university political scientist and an expert on east germany 
on the other hand sodaro added it puts the west in a 
position in which we dont really want to take excessive advantage 
of gorbachevs internal problems for fear that there might be a 
conservative backlash and gorbachev would be deposed he recognizes 
that the west has an interest in his continuation in power 
observers said they are sure that gorbachev in introducing 
relative freedom of expression and political action to the soviet 
domain did not anticipate the results 
he came to power dealing with not only the problems left to 
him by a communist regime that has failed but by russian history 
said arthur a hartman us amassador to moscow from 1981 to 1987 
i cant believe he didnt know he would have to deal with those 
problems on the other hand i dont think he predicted exactly the 
way things have gone 
janusz bugajski an eastern european specialist at the center 
for strategic and international studies said i dont think 
there was any preplanning for what happened in eastern europe 
there was no blueprint i think what happened was that gorbachev 
became educated during the late 80s as far as the likelihood of 
some major revolution 
sodaro said i think even the most farsighted advisers to 
gorbachev were stunned by the rapidity of the dissolution of 
communism in eastern europe and east germany 
the suddenness of those events he added is affecting the 
attitude of kremlin leaders toward developments in the baltic 
i dont think they want as rapid a disintegration of the 
remaining part of the empire sodaro said 
i think gorbachev from the outset wanted to purge the soviet 
system from the vestiges of stalinism and certainly the 
acquisition of the baltic states can be chalked up to stalin 
said sodaro i think in the back of his mind he and his advisers 
would have to expect this would happen but i dont really think 
that he intended from the outset to preside over the disintegration 
of the soviet empire 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP900522-0009 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
on this island where fantasy has long 
dictated policy reality is taking hold and may help improve 
relations with china and stimulate democratic change at home 
the myth has long been that the ruling nationalist party which 
retreated to taiwan after losing a civil war to communist forces in 
1949 is still the legitimate government of china 
that myth has long been used to justify the partys policy of no 
official contact with the rival government in beijing it also has 
long been used to justify the partys monopoly on political power 
but events of the past week culminating in the inaugural 
address of president lee tenghui on sunday indicate the days of 
fantasy are drawing to a close 
lee was sworn in for a sixyear term after being elected by the 
electoral college and stressed his commitment to democracy 
the nationalist government still calls itself the republic of 
china and says reunification with the chinese mainland is the 
ultimate goal 
but on wednesday hau said something no top official had 
previously acknowledged in public the reality is that china today 
is one country with two governments 
in his inauguration speech lee urged markedly improved 
relations with beijing and channels of communication that could 
eventually lead to talks on reunification 
in effect lee signaled a desire to end the 40yearold 
hardline policy toward the chinese communists known as the three 
nos no official contact no negotiations and no compromise 
there is a catch the nationalists want beijing to renounce the 
threat of force against taiwan end its policy of isolating taiwan 
diplomatically and scrap oneparty communist rule 
china on monday rejected such preconditions saying lee was 
ignoring the universally accepted fact that the peoples republic 
of china is the sole legitimate government representing all chinese 
people 
while taiwan does not expect an immediate breakthrough its 
leaders hope relations will improve as civilian and business 
contacts expand indirect trade across the taiwan straits was 4 
billion last year and taiwan residents made 1 million visits to 
the chinese mainland since such travel was first allowed in late 
1987 
we want gradually to expand our contact by peaceful ways 
government spokesman shaw yuming recently told foreign 
journalists we have to move in measured steps its not a 
very actionpacked kind of approach 
lee also said he wanted to quickly scrap the 1947 mobilization 
for the supression of the communist rebellion 
not only would this mean taiwan would no longer view the beijing 
government as a rebel group but it would also lift temporary legal 
provisions that have guaranteed the nationalist party a lock on 
power 
under the provisions the legislature and electoral college are 
dominated by nationalists elected on mainland china before the 
civil war defeat the theory is they cannot be replaced until their 
constituencies are recaptured and new elections held 
but the mainlandelected parliamentarians are dying fast and the 
islands 20 million people 85 percent of whom are native 
taiwanese want a greater say in government 
lee on sunday gave a twoyear timetable for replacing the 
provisions with constitutional amendments that would establish a 
great model of political democracy for all times 
he also stressed the importance of securing fair competition 
among political parties indicating an understanding that future 
legitimacy must come from the people 
still the promise of greater democracy is viewed skeptically by 
many students and opposition party members they view lees 
decision to nominate the countrys only fourstar general as 
premier a step back toward the nationalists authoritarian past 
but the nomination of defense minister hau peitsun also is 
viewed less sinisterly as an attempt by lee to shore up his support 
among party elders and to crack down on rampant corruption and 
crime 
government spokesman shaw said military rule or a return to 
authoritanism would be impossible 
nobody in this land no party no group no individuals 
can turn the clock back he said military rule military 
dictatorship or even authoritariantype of politics cannot be 
accepted by our people 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
dan biers has been a news editor based in hong 
kong for the associated press since 1987 
</TEXT>
