will strip the communist party of all the property it was granted 
use of during the past four decades 
the decision monday followed a move three days earlier to freeze 
ownership of all buildings and other fixed assets owned by the 
communists who were ousted from power in a peaceful revolution 
last year 
the moves were likely to be highly popular in czechoslovakia 
where up to 100000 people have attended recent street rallies 
calling for the communists to give up their property and urging a 
ban on the party in upcoming free elections 
kvestoslava korinkova head of the governments inspection 
commission said all contracts for property used by the communists 
will be declared null and void on june 1 a week before the 
countrys first free elections in more than 40 years 
such contracts were very often made under strange 
circumstances ms korinkova said 
she said the property would be turned over to educational 
cultural health and other institutions or to other political 
parties 
she did not say how many buildings would be affected but she 
estimated the total value at 306 million 
last friday parliament froze 281 million in fixed assets of 
the communist party pending investigation of each acquisition 
korinkova said the acquisitions would be considered legal only 
if made before nov 17 1989 the start of the popular revolt 
against communist rule and only if paid for from party dues 
