band director george foreman raised his 
hands and let them drop in a quick downbeat summoning a brassy 
musical flourish from about two dozen trumpet trombone and tuba 
players 
the martial melody and its bouncy rhythm conjured a nostalgic 
picture from the turn of the century when thousands of brass bands 
performed on weekends at community parks all across the country 
but the fanfare being played at a recent rehearsal of the 
advocate brass band was newly written and some music observers say 
the 3yearold group and its music are part of a slow but steady 
revival of brass bands 
the band is preparing to play host for the great american brass 
band festival june 1617 the festival will be held at the city 
park in this central kentucky town known for its antique charm and 
victorianstyle homes 
this night however the musicians were getting ready for the 
debut performance of the newly composed the advocatemessenger 
march 
the song in the tradition of newspaper anthems such as the 
washington post march is named for the local daily paper the 
bands sponsor the group has a large collection of rarely heard 
marches named for a wide array of american papers 
as many as 20000 people are expected for the festival which 
will include a balloon race buggy rides and displays of antique 
cars and bicycles 
we want to capture the nostalgia of a concert in the park 
said foreman cochairman of the festival and managing director of 
the norton center for the arts at centre 
through much of the 19th century and into the 1920s the brass 
band was a familiar part of the american town the bands played at 
political rallies parades parties and concerts 
harpers magazine in the 1880s reported that there were 10000 
brass bands in the united states foreman said 
brass bands began to decline foreman believes because world 
war i took away many of the musicians and the advent of radio and 
phonographs gave people other entertainment opportunities 
paul droste president of the north american brass band 
association said there are about 60 brass bands in the country 
the association was formed in 1983 when the bands began to rebound 
after nearly dying out in the 1950s 
droste a music professor at ohio state university is also 
director of the brass band of columbus a britishstyle band that 
has been named champion of the association four times in the past 
five years 
