<TEXT>
nato should consider revamping its 
military structure by using multinational forces as us troop 
levels in europe are reduced us defense secretary dick cheney 
said today 
cheney taking part in his second nato defense ministers 
meeting in two weeks said the western alliance must adapt if an 
eastwest conventional arms pact is reached and the threat of war 
against the warsaw pact recedes 
if all present positive trends continue then we can 
contemplate new ways of doing business cheney told reporters 
aboard his plane en route to brussels 
i think based on a first look the notion of a multinational 
force has some appeal cheney said i think its worth 
pursuing 
cheney arrived in brussels today for a twoday meeting of nato 
defense ministers to discuss the alliances future military posture 
the ministers are holding a series of discussions in advance of 
a summit of nato leaders in july president bush proposed the 
summit as a way to discuss changes in the role of the north 
atlantic treaty organization in light of the upheaval sweeping 
eastern europe and the soviet union 
the defense ministers meeting comes at a time when german 
unification is advancing rapidly and pressure is growing in 
washington for sharp cuts in military spending and reductions in 
the 300000strong us force based in europe 
using multinational forces in nato could offer cost savings and 
ease nationalist sensitivities particularly in west germany where 
most nato troops are stationed said a senior defense official 
traveling with cheney 
such forces could also help blunt any drive to take a unified 
germany out of nato 
one way to emphasize the multilateral nature of the nato 
alliance is to have units that are composed of troops of various 
nations cheney said such a plan would also emphasize the fact 
that germany is not treated any differently than anyone else 
as an example cheney said a multinational corps could be formed 
with three divisions each from a different nation a us division 
is made up of about 15000 to 18000 soldiers 
at present nato land forces defend territory under a socalled 
layer cake formula by which an army from an allied nation 
defends a certain sector 
us forces for example are stationed primarily in southern 
and central west germany while french and british forces defend 
other regions 
with the elimination of the border between east and west 
germany such a system would have to be revamped 
under a multinational system us german or british soldiers 
could be dispersed among several nations said the senior defense 
official he spoke on condition of anonymity 
soldiers of multinational units could be based in britain or 
canada for training exercises the official said 
such an arrangement for example could help reduce complaints 
among the west german public west germans have grown increasingly 
irritated with nato military exercises and accidents caused by 
lowflying aircraft 
today there is the sense that germany is singled out because 
the majority of troops are on their soil the official said 
but the official cautioned that setting up multinational forces 
poses many problems including language barriers and varied weapons 
systems 
he said he expected the defense ministers to propose a study of 
the multinational force concept during their twoday session 
mainly they are trying to ask themselves how should nato 
look in this new environment in europe the official said 
