in 1974 garrity ordered the citywide busing of black and white 
children to integrate the citys schools the move sparked several 
years of busingrelated violence 
garrity said his final order in the case to be issued at an 
undetermined date will ensure that the quota remains in effect 
until minority teachers have achieved enough seniority to protect 
them from immediate layoffs 
several hundred city teachers are expected to be laid off 
because of budget cutbacks if minority quotas are eradicated 
black teachers fear they will be among the first to go because they 
have little seniority 
according to the boston teachers union contract layoffs are 
made solely on seniority the union has fought the continuation of 
the minority quota system 
garrity told the hearing that he wanted to end the courts 
direct involvement in the case because of a new school assignment 
plan implemented last year it goes into effect in september 
the principle reason for ending the involvement is that we 
dont have a plan anymore he said the controlled choice plan 
is in effect but its not the courts plan and we shouldnt be 
involved 
garrity monitored the citys compliance with the desegregation 
order until 1987 when a federal appeals court ruled that the 
schools were finally desegregated and gave control over student 
assignment back to the school committee 
</TEXT>
