<TEXT>
nato defense ministers met today to 
take a hard look at the military strategy that guided the western 
alliance during the cold war years but now may be outdated 
the north atlantic treaty organizations key twoday meeting was 
to review what us defense secretary dick cheney called new ways 
of doing business in an era of reduced eastwest tensions 
on monday west european defense ministers meeting separately 
at the alliance headquarters in brussels urged nato to adapt to 
the changing security environment 
the ministers said it was of crucial importance to decide 
what level of defense was needed in a changing world 
we consider that discussion in the alliance on these issues is 
timely the ministers said in a statement at the end of their 
talks 
they also said west european countries must prepare to pay more 
in common defense costs as the united states moves to substantially 
reduce its military presence in europe 
as an example of new nato strategy in response to the impending 
unification of germany cheney raised the idea of a nato corps with 
divisions from different nations 
such a force would also emphasize the fact that germany is 
not treated any differently than anyone else he told reporters 
aboard his flight to brussels 
if all present positive trends continue then we can 
contemplate new ways of doing business cheney said 
less than two weeks ago the nato defense ministers held a 
meeting of the alliances nuclear planning group in kananaskis 
canada and agreed that there was a diminishing need for 
battlefield nuclear weapons in europe 
their current meeting this time as the defense planning 
committee is part of a series of discussions among highlevel nato 
officials that will culminate in an early july summit between 
president bush and the other alliance leaders 
nato is under pressure to move toward a political rather than a 
military role in an era of reduced eastwest tensions 
i think everybody accepts that business as usual is not 
possible said a nato diplomat discussing the meeting on 
condition of anonymity 
the defense officials were expected to take a look at the actual 
threat now posed by the sovietled warsaw pact the status of 
conventional arms reduction negotiations in vienna austria 
shrinking military budgets and the increased use of multinational 
forces 
they also will likely discuss their strategy of forward defense 
brought into question by the prospect of a united germany 
forward defense refers to the stationing of troops to defend the 
front line during an attack the idea is to defend territory at its 
border and not give up any land to invading soldiers the border 
between east and west germany soon to be erased is now considered 
part of the front line 
the ministers will likely call for studies of some of these 
issues as they review their future strategy 
there are many things which have been done for 40 years in a 
certain way which need to be revisited said the nato diplomat 
the ministers were considered certain to scrap a guideline in 
effect since the late 1970s that called for increasing military 
spending by 3 percent annually 
many countries have failed to meet that goal in recent years 
with easing tensions even fewer will hit the target now some 
countries like greece and turkey may keep spending up because of 
regional problems rather than fears of soviet aggression 
the ministers also will be asked to endorse defense plans based 
on an assessment of the current military threat posed by the soviet 
union said a senior nato official also on condition of anonymity 
he said the alliance needs to adopt a degree of prudence 
because of the uncertainty of the political upheaval in the east 
bloc but he said it also needs to be flexible to respond to future 
changes 
all 16 nato nations except france are represented at the 
meeting france is not a member of the alliances integrated 
military structure iceland which has no armed forces attends as 
an observer 
