<TEXT>
the senate agriculture committee voted tuesday 
for a bill that would require that fish processed as food be 
inspected in much the same way as meat and poultry 
currently less than 12 percent of american seafood undergoes 
some kind of inspection or grading said sen patrick leahy 
dvt chairman of the committee only 7 percent of almost 2000 
seafood processors nationwide participate in these voluntary 
inspection programs 
meat and poultry undergo rigorous inspection by the agriculture 
department 
a consumer advocate who has been campaigning since 1986 for 
similar standards for fish praised the bill but said it was 
missing two essential features 
ellen haas founder of public voice for food and health policy 
said she hoped to see an amendment added on the senate floor that 
would require fishing boats to be inspected 
she also said she was disappointed the committee removed 
whistleblower provisions in the bill that would have protected any 
employees of inspection programs who call attention to alleged 
misconduct or deficiencies 
they are the insurance of a program with integrity said 
haas senator leahy said he is committed to fight for it on the 
floor 
haas said the bill is strong as it stands but gives a great 
deal of responsibility to the industry 
similar legislation is pending in the house but has not yet 
been approved by the agriculture committee there 
under the senate bill the agriculture department would 
set standards for processing fish 
determine sources of potential contamination 
require prevention and cleanup procedures for contaminated 
areas 
assure through inspections that fish and food made from fish 
are processed under sanitary conditions 
the food and drug administration which administers the limited 
fish inspection program that exists would continue to decide the 
level of contamination that is considered harmful 
the commerce secretary would be authorized to close waters that 
are considered too contaminated for safe fishing 
imported fish would have to comply with all the standards set 
for fish harvested domestically 
grants totalling 2 million would be provided each year to 
educate fish processors on proper handling methods 
