<TEXT>
congress is going after the gasoline in your 
cars fuel tank as lawmakers try to clean up the nations 
smogclogged air 
what the fuel of the future will be is unclear but one thing 
seems certain something other than conventional gasoline will run 
the car of the late 90s 
tougher auto pollution controls that will be included in clear 
air legislation now before congress for the first time not only 
requires new control technology on automobiles but demands that 
oil companies change the chemistry of their gasoline so the fuel 
burns cleaner 
smogcausing pollutants will be reduced as will toxic emissions 
the bills also are being crafted to open the way for an array of 
gasoline alternatives including alcohol fuel blends such as 
methanol and ethanol and in some cases pure methanol compressed 
natural gas or propane 
proponents of the various fuels are lobbying intensely for 
provisions that might give them an edge 
the oil industry has spent 1 million in recent months for a 
thusfar unsuccessful effort to thwart provisions that could 
require ethanol blended gasoline in some of the largest cities that 
account for more than a fifth of the nations gasoline market 
the legislation already approved by the senate and a similar 
version coming to a vote this week in the house will require that 
gasoline meet tougher emission standards 
the petroleum industry hopes to meet those requirements by 
reworking the gasolines chemistry so that aromatics the chemicals 
that boost octane are replaced by cleaner additives 
some oil companies including arco and shell already have begun 
selling reformulated gasoline in some limited markets 
some members of congress say that doesnt go far enough 
a compromise agreement announced in the house this week requires 
even cleaner fuels to be sold in areas with serious smog problems 
the provisions similar to one in the senate bill require 
reformulated gasoline to have a certain oxygen content likely to 
be achieved by adding ethanol if it is sold in nine cities with 
the greatest smog problems and in 44 cities with excessive levels 
of carbon monoxide during some months of the year 
it will not ony clean up the nations air but give credibility 
to the growing ethanol industry said rep bill richardson 
dnm sponsor of the amendment 
some estimates say the provisions could more than double the 
demand for ethanol which is made from grain 
the oil industry argues the government should not impose a 
recipe for motor fuels and has vigorously fought not only efforts 
to require the use of ethanol but also methanol another 
alternative fuel derived from natural gas 
automakers say they are developing cars that run on methanol 
blends a mixture of as much as 85 percent methanol and 15 percent 
gasoline 
however both the auto and oil industries are opposed to pushing 
too quickly the sale of vehicles that burn only fuels other than 
gasoline 
the house this week will consider an amendment to the clean air 
bill by rep henry waxman dcalif that would require automakers 
by 1997 to build 1 million cars a year powered by a fuel other than 
gasoline and sell them in the nine cities with the worst smog 
problems 
those cities are los angeles chicago houston san diego 
philadelphia baltimore new york city hartford conn and 
milwaukee 
president bush made a similar suggestion a year ago but the 
white house backed away from the production mandate under intense 
pressure from the auto industry attempts to impose such a mandate 
failed in the senate but both environmentalists and auto lobbyists 
say the house vote could be close 
the aim is to cut total smogcausing emissions from those cars 
by 75 percent a requirement the auto industry says can only be 
achieved by making cars that run either entirely on methanol or on 
compressed natural gas 
the automakers have vigorously fought a production requirement 
for alternative fuel cars fearful that consumers may not buy them 
because of concern about reliability and the availability of fuels 
were talking about 30 or 40 percent of the vehicles sold in 
the nine cities its a preposterous notion said robert 
liberatore a lobbyist for the chrysler corp 
oil companies fear losing market share in a 100 billion annual 
gasoline business to the natural gas industry if the congress 
requires production of cars that cant meet emission standards by 
burning even reformulated gasoline 
