<TEXT>
the united states wants a new 
attackproof embassy compound in kuwait but acquiring one is 
turning out to be a diplomatic headache 
the present compound bounded by a hotel and the waters of the 
persian gulf has been deemed a security risk also the landlord 
does not want to renew the lease 
but replacing it could cost 32 million for the land alone a 
price tag that is raising eyebrows in washington relocation 
efforts are further complicated by kuwaits ban on real estate 
purchases by foreigners 
the compound which contains the ambassadors residence and the 
embassy was fortified after shiite moslem terrorists rammed a 
bombladen truck into its gates in december l983 
despite safeguards including concrete blockades and a high 
barbedwire fence that is electrified at some points security is 
not exactly airtight said an arab diplomat speaking on 
condition of anonymity 
the site was rented in the early 1950s from a landlord who is a 
ruling emir of one of the gulf states according to sources now a 
boom has driven the lands value up to an estimated 13 million 
and the landlord has given notice that the lease will not be 
renewed when it expires in 1995 
some lawmakers say even if the lease werent coming up security 
concerns alone would justify a new mission 
