<TEXT>
the peace corps nearly 30 years after its 
founding by president john f kennedy suffers from lingering 
perceptions it is a white middleclass institution congress was 
told tuesday 
only about 7 percent of the agencys roughly 6300 volunteers 
are minorities a congressional investigative agency found and 
through 1988 no minorities held any of the top 20 management jobs 
at the agency 
efforts to improve the peace corps minority profile in the 
past have been shortlived and costly the general accounting 
office said it called for a longterm strategy to correct the 
problem 
the underrepresentation of minorities in the peace corps has 
made it difficult for the agency to teach foreign peoples about the 
racially diverse american culture the study said 
congressional researchers acknowledged however that the peace 
corps has historically experienced great difficulty attracting 
sufficient number of minorities to serve as volunteers 
part of the problem stems from the lower economic status of 
blacks and other minorities the study said who believe that 
they cannot afford to volunteer two years of their lives to peace 
corps service 
but it said that minorities also tend to see the peace corps 
as a white middleclass organization 
rep john conyers dmich chairman of a house government 
operations subcommittee examining the peace corps program said the 
agency must work toward better portraying the united states to 
the people of the beneficiary countries by providing opportunities 
to ethnic and racial groups which would represent the amalgamation 
of our many rich cultures 
the gao report released as the house panel held a public 
hearing also said the agency was failing to meet a 1985 
congressional mandate to build its volunteer force to 10000 
during its heyday the peace corps in the mid1960s had a 
volunteer force as high as 16000 and a 114 million annual budget 
but the agency was given less money and saw its volunteer force 
shrink to 5000 at the start of the 1980s 
by this fall the gao report said the agency expects to have 
6700 volunteers in 76 countries 
several lawmakers noted that president bush sought a 9 percent 
increase in the agencys fiscal 1991 budget but they said more 
will be needed if the peace corps is to move people swiftly into 
eastern europe while continuing a heavy presence in third world 
nations 
if we expect the peace corps to meet the challenges and 
increasing responsibilities ahead then we need to ensure that the 
appropriate resources are available for the agency to realize its 
goals said conyers 
sen christopher dodd dconn a former peace corps volunteer 
who appeared as a witness before the subcommittee said the agency 
has received requests for volunteers from hungary poland 
czechoslovakia romania and east germany 
the peace corps needs the resources to respond to these 
requests from eastern europe he said but it cannot rob other 
parts of the world to accommodate an area of the world to which the 
peace corps has not previously been invited 
