<TEXT>
a railroad strike in northwestern poland 
spread tuesday and the government ordered the army to transport 
people and food 
the strike began sunday and the solidarityled government of 
prime minister tadeusz mazowiecki continued to appeal to rail 
workers to return to work 
the solidarity leadership met in gdansk to draft a response to 
the strike organized without the unions endorsement 
the government has rejected negotiations because the strikers 
are not operating through their unions it also said that giving in 
to their pay raise demands could scuttle postcommunist polands 
economic reforms 
strikes were reported tuesday at eight key depots including 
slupsk and koszalin near the baltic coast there were warning 
strikes and support actions in other provinces but precise numbers 
of those who walked off the job were not immediately available 
the workers began striking sunday night in support of more than 
three dozen colleagues on fasts some of the hunger strikers have 
been fasting since may 10 three were reported to have been 
hospitalized and others joined the protest monday pap said 
a team of doctors dispatched tuesday by the ministry of health 
was under orders to hospitalize any other workers whose health was 
in danger 
only one rail route was open to polands busiest port in 
szczecin and mail lines were paralyzed more than 160 local 
trains 47 freight trains and 14 longdistance passenger trains 
were canceled monday the official pap news agency reported 
the government decided to use the military to transport goods 
especially perishables according to news reports 
the army and the railway authority were also directed to 
organize alternative bus and truck transport for passengers and 
goods pap said 
the strike was the most serious labor unrest since the 
prodemocratic reforms which included unpopular austerity 
measures went into effect on jan 1 the reforms have reduced 
buying power by 40 percent and cut subsidies to stateowned 
enterprises including railroads 
labor minister jacek kuron met late monday with national railway 
authorities and news reports said it was agreed that no government 
money was available to raise average pay of 79 per month that is 
close to the national average but less than the pay in many 
industries the news reports said 
the strikers are demanding their salaries be raised to 110 
percent of the national average or another 8 this month but 
these figures are adjusted monthly to keep up with inflation 
the government in trying to control inflation has rejected pay 
or benefit increases that cannot be supported by the budgets of the 
enterprises or the government 
the strike represents a challenge to solidarity which has been 
trying to define its role in society whether it should focus on 
serving as a trade union backing workers or a political party 
supporting the government 
solidarity leader lech walesa reiterated his contention that the 
government his movement created was moving too slowing with reforms 
and failing to win the understanding of working poles 
the slupsk strike committee spokesman jerzy sadka said the 
workers support mazowiecki and do not consider their action 
political we are involved in purely worker and thus trade 
union issues and we protest against pulling us into political 
affairs he said 
