white house and congressional negotiators 
moved toward a consensus on tuesday that they must find about 500 
billion in new taxes and spending cuts over the next five years to 
balance the budget participants said 
at the third round of highlevel deficitreduction talks in the 
capitol the bush administration also unveiled a new higher 
estimate of the costs of rescuing the savings and loan industry 
the administration now says the bailout could cost as much as 61 
billion next year participants said about 11 billion higher than 
previous estimates 
democrats and republicans remained divided over precisely how 
much savings would be needed to balance the budget within five 
years democrats said 500 billion or more was necessary citing 
estimates by the nonpartisan congressional budget office 
republicans said the total necessary could be between 400 
billion to 500 billion they relied on projections by the white 
houses office of management and budget which until now has been 
saying that an improving economy will allow the budget to be 
balanced by 1995 omb presented figures tuesday showing that unless 
