<TEXT>
the house agriculture committee voted tuesday 
to establish a national dairy program that guarantees farmers 
1010 per hundred pounds of milk as long as surpluses stay below 5 
billion pounds 
the section of the 1990 farm bill differs from a plan approved 
earlier by the panels subcommittee on livestock dairy and poultry 
that proposal included producer assessments and set up a 
twotiered price support system that would have given farmers one 
price for the bulk of their milk and a lesser price for the amount 
considered excess by the government 
rep charles stenholm dtexas chairman of the subcommittee 
said the bill brought before the full committee was changed because 
so many people in congress and the industry disagreed with the 
original plan 
this is an effort to allow everyone to have an opportunity to 
have their opinion heard said stenholm who presented the new 
plan with rep steve gunderson of wisconsin the ranking republican 
on the subcommittee 
this is a dairy support program to provide stability to 
producers said gunderson 
the two lawmakers successfully fought off amendments offered in 
committee that would have further redesigned the dairy program 
the government traditionally has supported dairy farmers by 
setting a price it will pay for storable dairy products such as 
cheese butter and nonfat dry milk that arent bought by 
processors in the open market 
however overproduction has been an expensive problem for the 
government that lawmakers have been trying to correct 
the plan adopted by the committee tuesday would maintain for the 
next five years the current price of 1010 per hundredweight of 
milk if surpluses bought up by the government are between 35 
billion and 5 billion pounds if surpluses fall below 35 billion 
the government would pay 1055 per hundredweight 
however if dairy farmers produce between 501 billion and 7 
billion pounds more than the market will bear the government will 
pay only 985 to 960 per hundredweight 
if more than 7 billion pounds of surpluses result in any one 
year of the fiveyear farm bill the agriculture department would 
be authorized to establish an inventory management program 
stenholm emphasized that the price support system does not 
include assessments or a rigid quota system these portions of the 
earlier version of the bill were considered its main problem 
</TEXT>
