<TEXT>
us defense secretary dick cheney and 
other nato defense chiefs on tuesday backed using their soldiers to 
form multinational armies in europe to keep nato solidarity alive 
the proposal if enacted would result in an overhaul of the 
40yearold pacts military structure 
supporters say it is aimed at producing renewed political 
support for the alliance among member nations as they face the 
evaporation of the warsaw pact and as they prepare to welcome a 
unified germany into their ranks 
given the changing threat there is no alternative said 
cmdr stefan lang a spokesman for the west german defense 
ministry existing forces will be hollowed out and we have to 
reconfigure them 
gen vigleik eide who serves as chairman of the alliances 
military committee formally declared natos primary military foe 
conquered at the morning session telling reporters it is our 
clear assessment that the threat from a united warsaw pact no 
longer exists 
but the norwegian general cautioned the soviet union despite 
its economic and political turmoil still wields forces that are 
very impressive and continues to modernize its forces 
given chances for reduced troop levels in europe with the 
completion of a proposed eastwest accord on conventional forces 
and prospects for sharp cuts in us troops based in europe the 
idea of using multinational military units in nato nations has 
garnered support among the defense ministers lang and other nato 
officials said 
the proposal was discussed as the ministers began a twoday 
session to review the pacts military strategy at this time of 
reduced eastwest tension 
during their conferences the ministers also agreed to take a 
thorough look at their military strategy that has guided the 
alliance through the cold war years 
we reached agreement on that said britains defense chief 
tom king were keen to see it go ahead 
italian defense minister mino martinazzoli said the study must 
be daring 
the officials said the study should take a look at the whole 
range of military practices that nato has followed for many years 
including exercises conventional and nuclear weapons and the 
deployment of forces along the front line which has been put in 
question by prospects of a unified germany 
the ministers also agreed in their closeddoor talks to scrap 
the defense spending guideline that calls for an annual 3 percent 
increase 
nato officials said they would also like to bring france which 
is outside the joint military structure into the alliances 
defense planning 
cheney speaking with reporters en route to brussels backed the 
idea of building multinational forces 
at present nato land forces defend territory under a socalled 
layer cake formula by which an army from an allied nation 
defends a certain geographic sector 
with the elimination of the border between east and west 
germany such a system would have to be revamped 
if all present positive trends continue then we can 
contemplate new ways of doing business cheney said 
i think based on a first look the notion of a multinational 
force has some appeal cheney said i think its worth 
pursuing 
using multinational forces in nato could offer cost savings and 
ease nationalist sensitivities particularly in west germany where 
most nato troops are stationed said a senior defense official 
traveling with cheney 
such forces could also help blunt any drive to take a unified 
germany out of nato 
one way to emphasize the multilateral nature of the nato 
alliance is to have units that are composed of troops of various 
nations cheney said such a plan would also emphasize the fact 
that germany is not treated any differently than anyone else 
as an example cheney said a multinational corps could be formed 
with three divisions each from a different nation a us division 
is made up of about 15000 to 18000 soldiers 
soldiers of multinational units could be based in britain or 
canada for training exercises the official said 
such an arrangement could help reduce complaints among west 
german citizens west germans have grown increasingly irritated 
with nato military exercises and accidents caused by lowflying 
aircraft 
but the official cautioned that setting up multinational forces 
poses many problems including language barriers and varied weapons 
systems 
</TEXT>
