<DOCNO> AP900522-0193 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
yasser arafat chairman of the palestine 
liberation organization wanted the bush administration to allow 
him to attend a un security council session in new york city 
us officials said tuesday 
but the question apparently became moot during the evening the 
arab league said in new york the security council would meet in 
geneva to hear arafat as it did once before and an announcement 
was expected from un officials 
arafat made an indirect request for an entry visa in a letter to 
un secretarygeneral javier perez de cuellar with the expectation 
it would be passed on to the state department 
the united states denied arafat a visa two years ago for a 
similar mideast debate at the united nations 
us officials speaking on condition of anonymity said no 
decision had been made because the situation was hypothetical 
it would remain hypothetical if the department passed word back to 
the plo that the visa request would be denied 
were hearing reports a formal application will be made but 
as of this briefing we have not received anything margaret d 
tutwiler the state department spokeswoman told reporters at 
midday 
if arafat had gone to the united nations the plos stature 
would have been elevated dramatically that would come at a time 
when israel is being pressured even by friends such as the united 
states because of the force it has used to try to stem a violent 
uprising by palestinian arabs on the west bank and in gaza 
when the reagan administration refused to allow arafat to attend 
a un general assembly session in november 1988 the debate was 
shifted to geneva a month later in an electrifying reversal of 
policy the administration opened talks with the plo 
arafat following us instructions had publicly renounced 
terrorism and said he recognized israels right to exist however 
the plo covenant still calls for dismantling the jewish state 
the state department told congress in march that the plo was 
adhering to its commitment renouncing terrorism 
in denying the plos application for a visa in 1988 despite 
overwhelming pressure from many other un members thensecretary 
of state george p shultz said the us government has convincing 
evidence that plo elements have engaged in terrorism against 
americans and other targets 
shultz also said that arafat knows of condones and lends 
support to such acts and is an accessory to such terrorism 
a month later shultz took the lead in opening us talks with 
the plo those talks are continuing in tunis the plo headquarters 
through egypt the plo has registered its terms for talks between 
palestinians and israel in cairo 
secretary of state james a baker iii has been unable to 
persuade israel to adopt the terms participation by exiled 
palestinians and by residents of east jerusalem 
israeli prime minister yitzhak shamir is trying to shut the plo 
out of the elections he has proposed for the west bank and gaza 
arafat speaking monday in baghdad iraq appealed to president 
bush to pressure israel to stop what the plo chairman described as 
atrocities against palestinians 
arafat rejected israeli claims that the lone israeli gunman who 
