<TEXT>
the odds are daunting for the 400 or so 
candidates who will challenge incumbent congressmen this november 
chances are fewer than a dozen will win 
discontent over the pay raise that house members voted 
themselves talk of a tax increase and ethical lapses could spell 
trouble for some members of congress 
but over the years few bets have been safer than a house 
incumbents reelection the success rate has been as high as 98 
percent in recent years and many believe the reelection rate will 
approach that figure this time around 
the two parties are jostling over about 30 open seats where 
no incumbent is running but otherwise this fall generally is 
viewed as a warmup for 1992 
thats when the pattern should break the redrawing of 
congressional districts and a surge in retirements will reshape the 
house giving republicans a rare chance to regain a house majority 
or to come close 
currently the house is controlled by democrats by a 257176 
margin with two vacancies 
basically the parties have written off the house in 1990 and 
are putting all their energies into 92 said thomas mann of the 
brookings institution a liberal think tank 
with all the advantages available to members of congress high 
reelection rates have become the norm for house races much more 
so than for senators 
members of congress have an arsenal of weapons to keep their 
names in front of voters taxpayerfinanced mail privileges a 
staff to help solve constituents problems ready access to news 
coverage and an overwhelming advantage in raising money 
lets face it said rep john g rowland rconn you have 
to be a bozo to lose this job 
some call this the permanent congress it is at the heart of 
political debates over campaign finance reform redistricting even 
proposals to limit house and senate members to 12 years in office 
rowland who is running for governor is among the handful 
bypassing likely reelection republicans stymied by 36 years in 
the minority are more frequently departing the house for other 
offices eight are running for the senate this year 
for those who choose to remain the odds are good 
the rate of reelection has been 98 percent or better in the 
last two election years and it was 96 percent in the face of the 
1984 republican presidential landslide the rate hasnt dipped 
below 90 percent since 1974 the watergate year that swept 
republicans out of congress 
over the last two election years only 15 out of more than 800 
candidates who challenged incumbents were successful 
a challengers best chance to overcome the odds comes when 
scandal befalls the incumbent of the seven incumbents who were 
