as part of a budget solution could confound some republican 
candidates plans to attack democrats as tax raisers ed rollins 
head of the republican congressional campaign committee called the 
tax talk a disaster for his candidates 
charles cook who publishes a political newsletter argues that 
a surprise may be in store for incumbents of both parties this year 
congress he figures has taken a beating over the pay raise 
savingsandloan scandals sex scandals and attention on speech 
fees and campaign money since speaker jim wright was forced to 
resign 
a potentially explosive combination of unrelated events and 
news stories with a single common thread are all extremely 
unflattering to congress cook said the result may well be a 
reelection rate closer to the normal 94 percent to 96 percent 
range 
both parties need skillful challengers to exploit any 
possibilities and recruiting good candidates has been a problem 
republicans in particular have had trouble and their longtime 
minority status in the house is only one reason 
its much easier for democrats to recruit a candidate than for 
the republicans said rep mickey edwards dokla republicans 
tend to be people who want government out of their lives 
theyre just not inclined 
money is the big obstacle for any challenger specialinterest 
political action committees or pacs tend to direct their money to 
the candidate most likely to win 
political campaigns today are determined by money media and 
personal influence said harold coker a republican who lost a 
1988 challenge in tennessee if you are in you have access to 
it all but if you are out youre just out of luck 
the high success rate for incumbents who seek reelection 
doesnt mean there isnt turnover in congress since some members 
opt to run for other office or retire 
the median number of terms served by house members in the 
current congress is just five or 10 years said the brookings 
institutions mann 
the changes expected in 1992 may bring as many as 80 to 100 new 
members redistricting will encourage retirements and could pit 
some incumbents against one another 
other incumbents may decide to take the money and run since 
1992 is the last year they can pocket their unspent campaign 
treasuries upon retirement 
