<DOCNO> AP900522-0203 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
fuzzy may not seem like a good feature for a 
camcorder but japanese electronics companies say fuzzy logic 
allows their new handheld video cameras to produce sharper 
jitterfree pictures 
the camcorders are the latest in a growing number of japanese 
consumer appliances to incorporate fuzzy logic which uses 
highpowered semiconductors to enable computers to reason more like 
humans and recognize the nuances of the real world 
the trend is yet another example of japanese manufacturers 
taking an innovation developed in the united states and 
incorporating it more rapidly in consumer goods 
most computers can process information only in yesno form 
such as black or white or near or far but fuzzy logic 
allows computers to think in degrees such as medium gray or 
rather close 
to make such distinctions the camcorders are packed with 
technology so much so that analysts say theyre in the same 
league as hardware used in military guidance systems or 
reconnaissance satellites 
in fact the devices share many of the same technologies ccd 
sensors that convert light images to digital signals digital 
pattern recognition circuits sophisticated semiconductors and 
computers all in superminiature size 
a camcorders microcomputer uses fuzzy logic to give more 
accurate autofocusing and autoexposure by responding more 
smoothly and quickly to changing conditions itaru ishizawa of 
sanyo electric co said 
sanyos vmes88 the first camcorder to use fuzzy logic sets 
the lens exposure by dividing the image into 64 parts by 
measuring the relative brightness of each part the camera can 
calculate the best exposure and compensate automatically for strong 
lighting in front or back of the subject he said 
most camcorders focus on whatever is in the middle of their 
field of view but the vmes88s fuzzy logic helps it stay focused 
when a subject moves away from the center ishizawa said 
the 8mm format camcorder weighs 17 pounds and is being sold in 
japan for the equivalent of 1060 sanyo plans to begin marketing 
it in the united states in july and in europe in the fall ishizawa 
said 
pentax is selling in japan under its own brand name a similar 
camcorder made by sanyo it has the additional feature of 
timelapse recording such as one frame every 10 seconds toshihiro 
tanaka of pentax said 
the company plans to begin sales in both the united states and 
europe in the fall he said 
matsushita electric industrials new camcorder takes a different 
hitech tack for sharpening images with an electronic image 
stabilizer 
the stabilizer reduces picture jitter caused by unsteady hands 
by digitally analyzing the cameras images and storing them in a 
memory it detects brief shifts from previous images resulting from 
camera shakes and recalls the earlier image from the memory to 
smooth out the picture matsushita said 
matsushita which uses the panasonic brand name overseas said 
it will begin selling the camcorder called nvs1 in japan next 
month for the equivalent of 1075 the unit which uses vhsc 
tapes weighs 16 pounds 
sony meanwhile has announced a video walkman component set 
with a separate camera deck monitor and tuner that can be used in 
any combination 
the 8mm format set featuring the worlds smallest and lightest 
video deck at 11 pounds and stereo sound will begin selling in 
japan in july for 1070 the company said 
fuzzy logic was first developed in the 1960s by lofti zadeh a 
professor at the university of california at berkeley but has won 
greater popularity in recent years in japan 
it guides elevators and subway trains to smooth starts and 
stops and helps sonys new keyboardless computer recognize 
thousands of handwritten japanese characters 
in recent months it even has appeared in the controls of washing 
machines where it measures the degree of dirt in the clothes and 
amount of laundry and in vacuum cleaners where it calculates the 
quantity of dust and type of floor 
fuzzy logics rapid rise in popularity among japanese 
manufacturers illustrates the fierce technological competition in 
japans marketplace it also shows how japanese companies struggle 
to develop a market for new technologies 
fuzzy logic is a difficult concept to explain to customers 
sanyos ishizawa said we generally explain that its a more 
human way of analyzing information 
the company has produced a videotape he said to explain the 
idea at stores selling the product 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

