tougher competition in the automotive 
industry threatens the united auto workers attempt to force a 
common contract on the nations big three automakers some analysts 
say 
for the first time in 11 years contracts between the uaw and 
general motors corp ford motor co and chrysler corp will expire 
at the same time midnight sept 14 
but the socalled pattern bargaining that characterized labor 
relations until 1979 may not be feasible in the hotly competitive 
1990s 
in the past decade us automakers have lost market share faced 
financial crises slashed costs joined with japanese companies in 
joint ventures closed factories and trimmed salaried and hourly 
work forces 
the moves were inspired at least in part by competition from 
japanese automakers first with cars imported from overseas and 
later with vehicles made in the united states 
as a result negotiating strategies have changed twenty years 
ago when the big three completely dominated the us market the 
uaw would pick one company as a target settle on a contract and 
then impose the terms the other two 
in turn that contract would serve as a model for other large 
industrial unions including steel and rubber workers 
but dale brickner of michigan state university says those days 
are over 
these firms have different cost factors they have different 
abilities to pay he said monday if a pattern means that you 
are going back to the years of xerox contracts those days are dead 
and gone 
uaw president owen bieber speaking after the first day of a 
threeday union bargaining convention in kansas city disagreed 
were not going to end pattern bargaining he said i just 
moved chrysler last time in 1988 to a common expiration date 
were not going to get off pattern 
in 1979 when chrysler was on the brink of financial ruin the 
no 3 automaker broke from the pattern chrysler today faces fresh 
financial problems and industry observers have said it again is the 
mostly likely company to break the newly revived pattern 
chryslers labor vice president anthony st john recently 
sounded an ominous tone when he said if the current contract is 
continued with no changes it would boost the struggling 
automakers labor costs by 16 percent 
that hinted at the possibility of chrysler seeking concessions 
from the uaw something the union reluctantly swallowed in the 
early 1980s chrysler workers returned to near pay parity with 
their counterparts at ford and gm in 1988 
this years negotiations brickner said will determine 
whether an old econmic pattern will continue at all with the 
japanese in there it aint the same game any more 
