<TEXT>
the finance minister today rejected 
opposition leaders demands for changes in the new economic treaty 
with east germany and warned that delaying unification could cause 
trigger unrest among east germans 
west german finance minister theodor waigel made his remarks in 
a speech to the upper house of parliament the bundesrat which 
began examining the treaty today 
waigel appealed to the opposition social democrats not to 
attempt to delay the july 2 target date on which the two germanys 
are to be merged into one economic entity 
his comments came a day after hansjochen vogel the social 
democrats national chairman told reporters his party wants to 
negotiate with chancellor helmut kohls government over improving 
the treatys terms for east germans 
the social democrats favor the economic merger but maintain the 
treaty as written is unfair to east germans 
but waigel told the bundesrat that rejection of the treaty could 
result in worsened social and economic conditions in east germany 
a new entrance into the basic discussions on the treatys 
terms could seriously place east germanys economic health in 
question waigel said 
it could also heap up social problems and social 
explosives because of east german hopes for a better standard of 
living after economic union he said 
whoever rejects this treaty must assume the moral political 
and historic responsibiity if german unity is gambled away for a 
limitless time waigel said 
the social democrats position could spell trouble for the 
economic merger treaty which was signed friday at a ceremony in 
bonn 
the treaty must still be approved by the parliaments of both 
countries the social democrats recently won control of the upper 
house in west germanys parliament by defeating kohls christian 
democrats in two key state elections 
the bundesrat is expected to vote on the treaty june 22 the 
lower house or bundestag is scheduled to vote on ratifying the 
treaty on june 21 
volker ruehe the head of kohls christian democrats accused 
the social democrats of displaying an alarming amount of 
irresponsibility 
he appealed to the opposition party not to let in a dangerous 
risk for the future of all germans and not to reject the state 
treaty on economic merger 
vogel told reporters the social democrats cannot accept the 
proposed treaty in its present form because it falls short in 
helping create modern and qualified jobs for east germans and 
guarding against the collapse of east german businesses 
according to vogel the social democrats are demanding changes 
or amendments either within or outside the treaty text 
that seemed to leave open the possibility the treaty could be 
approved as is with additions to be worked out later 
vogel said the social democrats would determine their final 
position on the proposed treaty in light of answers to our 
demands 
the social democrats could use their majority in the upper house 
to slow approval of the treaty however they could also decide it 
is not in their best political interests to actually block the 
merger since that could cost them votes when joint german 
elections are held possibly at the end of this year 
east germanys own social democrats the sister party of the 
west german group say they will not try to block the treaty the 
east german social democrats are part of their countrys coalition 
government and participated in the treaty negotiations 
under the merger treaty west germanys mark will become east 
germanys own legal tender as of july 2 east germany will also 
start scrapping its centrally planned economy for one that mirrors 
west germanys 
thousands of east germans are already worried they could be hit 
hard by their nations economic overhaul many east german 
staterun factories are expected to shut down when they are forced 
to compete in a free market and hundreds of thousands of workers 
are likely to lose their jobs 
