<TEXT>
a colorado savings and loan that counted one 
of president bushs sons as a director made inflated loans to 
developers who had to reinvest part of the money in the thrift 
federal regulators said today 
the house banking committee opened two days of hearings on the 
1 billion collapse of the silverado banking savings and loan 
association of denver bushs son neil and other former board 
members are to testify on wednesday 
a panel of thrift regulators told the committee they found a 
quid pro quo lending program at silverado under which 
developers received loans to buy buildings at inflated values set 
by outside appraisers 
the properties values had been inflated 270 million to 300 
million they said 
the regulators told the banking committee that silverados board 
of directors operated as a rubber stamp for management they 
also said insider abuse occurred at the thrift 
because management of silverado took excessive risks engaged 
in abusive or questionable practices to generate shortterm gains 
and undertook innovative manipulations to avoid recording losses 
the role of the directors was even more crucial the regulators 
statement said throughout silverados history the board did 
little beyond rubberstamping the activities of its sophisticated 
bright and manipulative management team 
the panel of regulators testifying today included stephen p 
hershkowitz deputy director of enforcement at the office of thrift 
supervision and brian c mccormally terry sandefur and dorothy 
van cleave of the ots district office in topeka kan 
kermit mowbray former president of the federal home loan bank 
of topeka did not appear and gonzalez said he would ask the 
committee to subpoena mowbray who is in greece 
in exchange for receiving loans bigger than the market price of 
the buildings the developers were required to use the surplus part 
of the loan money to buy preferred stock in silverados holding 
company or to purchase an interest in a loan pool set up by the 
thrift 
the pool which contained both good and bad loans totaled 
around 1 billion or roughly 60 percent of silverados total loan 
portfolio the developers who bought shares in the loan pool 
received interest generated by the performing loans in the pool 
examiners said monday they believed this arrangement was unique 
in the sampl industry 
federal regulators declined to say monday whether the 
appraisers who included accounting firms coopers amp lybrand and 
ernst amp young also were under investigation 
government investigators said monday they believe robert m 
lewis former vice chairman and chief financial officer of 
silverado was the financial guru who probably invented the 
concept of the loan pool 
the december 1988 collapse of silverado now operating as part 
of columbia savings the largest thrift in colorado is expected to 
cost us taxpayers as much as 1 billion total losses from the 
nationwide savings and loan crisis which has forced the government 
to take over more than 400 failed institutions are estimated at 
around 250 billion 
the connections among silverado and other insolvent sampls are 
being examined the others include charles h keating jrs lincoln 
savings and loan association and the junk bond operation of former 
drexel burnham lambert inc financier michael milken 
ots has alleged that loans by silverado to neil bushs business 
partners developers kenneth good and bill walters represented a 
conflict of interest for bush 34 who was a director of silverado 
from 1985 to august 1988 he resigned two weeks after his father 
received the republican presidential nomination 
in january regulators began disciplinary procedures against 
bush that could result in a lifetime ban from the financial 
institutions industry bush who has denied any wrongdoing said 
early this month he will cooperate with congress the ots and any 
other agencies involved 
examiners at the ots have expressed concern about silverados 
heavy investments in colorados ailing commercial real estate 
market 
they also have focused on what they said was an exceptionally 
large number of problem transactions between silverado insiders 
and borrowers 
bush who was a partner in an oil exploration firm jnb 
exploration had business deals with two of silverados major 
borrowers good and walters 
bush has said he did not benefit directly or indirectly from any 
loan or transaction between silverado and businesses controlled by 
walters who had a 625 percent limited partnership interest in jnb 
exploration bush has said he voted in 1986 with the other 
directors in unanimously approving the walters loans brought to 
them by management because there was no conflict of interest under 
federal banking laws or colorado regulations 
good and walters are scheduled to testify at wednesdays hearing 
along with michael r wise the former chairman of silverado 
richard k vanderpool silverados former vice chairman and 
chief operating officer also is expected to appear wednesday 
along with lewis and other former directors besides bush 
