<TEXT>
by elaine kurtenbachequals 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
a dispute over how fast japan will liberalize 
interest rates on deposits could make banking the next area of 
trade tensions in coming months a senior us official said 
tuesday 
after two days of talks with japanese officials on financial 
reforms us undersecretary of the treasury david c mulford said 
japans refusal to finish deregulating interest rates within one 
year was beginning to look more and more like a trade problem 
the deregulation process for interest rates is the key to all 
other liberalization and it is necessary for developing a money 
market policy mulford said 
he said that after seven years of stepbystep transition us 
officials would like the process of deregulation to be wrapped up 
within a year 
the talks led by mulford and his japanese counterpart vice 
minister of finance makoto utsumi were the eighth in a series of 
discussions on reforming the two countries financial markets 
separately the japanese government and ruling party on tuesday 
adopted a new economic policy guideline aimed at meeting other 
promises made in recent trade talks with the united states 
the new guideline calls for opening japans markets to more 
foreign goods making fiscal and budgetary policy changes to 
conform with other trading partners and increasing foreign aid 
on the interestrate front us officials charge that japanese 
financial firms take advantage of open markets overseas while 
receiving government protection from foreign competition at home 
while interest rates for money market certificates and largelot 
time deposits have been partially liberalized since 1984 when the 
bilateral talks began the ceilings on rates for demand deposits 
and smaller time deposits remain low time deposits account for 
about threequarters of total bank deposits here according to 
industry estimates 
utsumi said japanese officials agreed on the need to completely 
liberalize interest rates but disagreed on timing 
he bluntly disagreed with us charges that interest rate 
controls were being retained to give japanese banks a source of 
artificially cheap capital for loans and other investments 
enabling them to expand their presence overseas 
to avoid foreign exchange exposure loans overseas are made 
with funds in the same currency the loans are denominated in 
utsumi said 
utsumi declined to explain why japan would not specify a 
timetable for its plans and refused to comment on reports that 
interest rate ceilings would be lifted by 1993 
mulford said the failure to produce a timetable was likely to 
fuel protectionist moves in congress 
foreign banks share in total bank deposits in japan has risen 
only from 09 percent in 1983 to 104 percent in 1988 while their 
share of loans has fallen from 357 percent to 188 percent the 
bank of japan says 
japans share in the us lending market meanwhile has grown 
from 74 percent in 1983 to 14 percent in 1989 
the treasury department is required by law to report to congress 
by dec 1 on whether japan and other countries have given us 
banks and brokerages the same access they receive in american 
financial markets 
the fair trade and financial services act being considered in 
congress calls for retaliatory action against foreign financial 
firms in the united states if their own governments do not give 
us companies reciprocal treatment 
as of today it will not be possible for the us treasury to 
give a positive report on the japanese market mulford said 
analysts say the finance ministry faces strong opposition to 
interest rate deregulation from small and mediumsize banks already 
facing difficulties due to higher interest rates and limited 
liberalization 
japans central bank has raised its key rate for loans to 
commercial banks from 25 percent to 525 percent in the past year 
in turn commercial banks prime lending rates jumped from about 
55 percent to 72 percent 
finance ministry officials did promise to approve new foreign 
exchangerelated and securitized financial products and allow 
foreign securities firms to establish banking facilities to handle 
foreign exchange services mulford said 
the japanese also pledged to approve the use of the globex 
trading system by the end of june globex is a global electronic 
automated system for the trading of futures and futures options 
jointly operated by the chicago mercantile exchange and reuters 
holdings plc 
but we still see most of these improvements as only 
intermediate steps which fail to lead to complete financial market 
liberalization he said 
</TEXT>
