<TEXT>
the senate on monday approved a 
constitutional change that will allow the return of private 
commercial banking the government news agency notimex said 
the reform repeals the 1982 nationalization of the banking 
system it eliminates a paragraph in the constitution that reserved 
ownership of banking and credit services for the government 
proposed may 2 by president carlos salinas de gortari and passed 
earlier by the chamber of deputies the legislation will be sent to 
the countrys 31 states approval by 16 of the state legislatures 
is required 
the reform passed the senate on a 522 vote 
in the 90minute debate two senators from the leftist 
democratic revolutionary party opposed the bill arguing that it 
runs counter to national interests and will concentrate economic 
power in the hands of a few 
sen alfonso martinez dominguez of the ruling institutional 
revolutionary party which holds all but four of the 64 senate 
seats responded that the reforms are in response to world changes 
under the change up to 100 percent private ownership will be 
allowed in the 18 commercial banks affected but salinas has said 
the government would retain stock in some commercial banks the 
government also will keep numerous banks and other institutions 
that provide farm and development loans and other specialized 
services 
when thenpresident jose lopez portillo nationalized the banking 
system in september 1982 as he neared the end of his term he 
claimed the banks were helping mexicans send money out of the 
country sinking the economy deeper into recession 
in proposing the return to private banking salinas said the 
country has made sweeping changes in development policies and 
economic structure to emerge from the economic crisis 
since salinas took office in december 1988 hundreds of 
stateowned businesses and industries have been closed or put up 
for sale to private interests the countrys onceheavily protected 
domestic markets have been opened up to foreign competition and 
doors have been reopened to foreign investment 
also on monday a senate report recommended mexico negotiate a 
free trade agreement with the united states its largest trading 
partner give high priority to trade with the pacific basic 
countries and review agreements with japan to include new forms of 
cooperation and investment 
