<TEXT>
kidder peabody amp co has announced it would 
resume for its own accounts a form of program trading blamed for 
worsening stock market volatility a newspaper reported 
kidder said it believed it can avoid disrupting the market with 
safeguards it is adopting the new york times said in an early 
edition of tuesdays newspaper 
kidder and other wall street brokerages stopped employing a type 
of program trading known as index arbitrage after the stock market 
plunged last october the strategy seeks to profit from small 
differences in prices between the stock and futures markets by 
simultaneously buying and selling big baskets of stocks and stock 
index futures 
kidder a subsidiary of general electric co said it wouldnt 
use the strategy during times of high volatility 
it also said it would require that stock sales would be made as 
part of program trades only if the last trade on the new york stock 
exchange took place at a higher price than the previous one and 
purchases would be made only if the last big board trade was done 
at a lower price than previously 
whatever we do will be done more slowly and we will surely do 
less than we would have done without the restrictions thomas f 
ryan executive managing director of kidder was quoted as saying 
although other brokerages have continued to conduct program 
trades for clients the only wall street firm to do so for its own 
accounts has been bear stearns amp co 
</TEXT>
