silverado made inflated loans to developers who had to reinvest 
part of the money in the thrift 
thrift regulators told the committee that under the quid pro 
quo lending program at silverado developers received loans to 
buy buildings at inflated values set by outside appraisers 
the properties values were inflated by 270 million to 300 
million over market value they said 
in exchange developers were required to use part of the loan 
money to buy preferred stock in silverados holding company to 
purchase an interest in a loan pool set up by the thrift 
the pool which contained both good and bad loans totaled 
around 1 billion or roughly 60 percent of silverados total loan 
portfolio developers who bought shares in the loan pool received 
interest generated by the performing loans in the pool 
examiners said monday they believed this arrangement set up in 
august 1986 was unique in the sampl industry 
the panel of regulators told the banking committee that 
silverados board of directors was a rubber stamp for 
management they also said insider abuse occurred at the thrift 
neil bush had oil and gas business deals with two of silverados 
major borrowers developers kenneth good and bill walters 
