<TEXT>
proponents of a federal law that might make it 
more difficult for victims of defective products to collect damages 
overcame a major obstacle tuesday when a key committee voted to 
approve the proposal 
sen ernest hollings dsc chairman of the commerce science 
and transportation committee and consumer subcommittee chairman 
sen richard bryan dnev both opposed the bill but backers 
picked up support from other democrats in the 137 vote 
this is what we never had before this is what is new said 
victor schwartz an attorney for business and industry supporters 
of the legislation who said the support from sen lloyd bentsen 
was especially important 
this is very bipartisan now he said 
congress has tried to develop a federal product liability law 
since the 1970s and president bush made it an administration 
legislative priority in his state of the union address 
the bill would create a uniform standard for imposing punitive 
damages in product liability lawsuits and establish a twoyear 
statute of limitations for most product liability claims claims by 
workers injured by durable goods such as factory machinery would 
have a 25year statute of limitations 
the measure would allow separate trials or settlements of 
punitive damages and compensatory damages and allow companies to 
pay some noneconomic damages in proportion to their responsibility 
for harm 
it would also exempt from punitive damage lawsuits products 
approved by the food and drug administration and the federal 
aviation administration 
opponents say the bill would needlessly preempt state law and 
would limit the ability to collect for deaths and injuries that 
result from industry negligence or irresponsibility 
backers of the legislation argue that variations in liability 
laws from state to state offer potentially limitless damages and 
hinder product development and american competitiveness 
the bill will not go immediately go to the senate because it has 
been referred to the judiciary committee proponents say the bills 
prospects there are uncertain however there is a companion bill 
hr2700 in the house 
schwartz said some opponents may attempt a filibuster if the 
bill reaches the senate floor for debate 
besides bentsen dtexas democratic senators voting to report 
the bill favorably out of committee were daniel inouye of hawaii 
nebraskas james exon jay rockefeller of west virginia and charles 
s robb of virginia 
republicans voting for the bill were wisconsins robert w 
kasten jr john danforth of missouri larry pressler of south 
dakota ted stevens of arkansas john mccain of arizona conrad 
burns of montana slade gorton of washington and trent lott of 
mississippi 
joining hollings and bryan in voting against the bill were 
sens wendell ford dky john kerry dmass al gore dtenn 
john breaux dla and robert packwood rore 
</TEXT>
