with the first quarter of 1989 mainly because of provisions made 
to cover the possibility that they will be unable to collect 
accrued and unpaid interest from vms 
the funds have severed their ties to chicagobased vms a 
limited partnership syndicator that disclosed a severe liquidity 
crisis last year 
the funds had raised 11 billion from the public and lent it to 
vms to invest in realestate development 
in february vms stopped making loan payments to the funds and 
four vms officers resigned 
vmss troubles resulted partly from the softening real estate 
market and from changes in the federal tax law in 1986 that made 
real estate investments less attractive xerox corp holds a 25 
percent interest in vms 
