<TEXT>
two soviet officials predicted 
their nations energy exports to western and eastern europe would 
drop in the next few years because soviet oil natural gas and coal 
are becoming too expensive to produce 
petroleum and gas exports could drop to as little as one third 
of their 1988 levels according to alexander a arbatov a member 
of the committee for natural resources of the soviet academy of 
sciences and foreign ministry official eugene m khartukov 
in that year the soviet union exported the energy equivalent of 
447 million tons of coal the two officials said in a joint written 
presentation at the seventh petroleum and gas conference here 
energy exports have ceased bringing in golden eggs for 
the soviet economy the paper said 
the soviets have earned a significant amount of hard currency by 
exporting energy to western europe particularly west germany 
italy and austria eastern europe relies almost exclusively on the 
soviets for energy imports 
the paper gave no specific reason for the rising cost of energy 
production 
western experts however have said that moscow has failed to 
invest in modern equipment and is being forced to drill for oil and 
gas on remote siberian locations as more easily accessible sources 
become depleted 
in 1981 the soviet union made 71 times as much from the sale 
of a barrel of crude petroleum as it cost to produce the oil the 
two officials paper said 
by next year that ratio will have fallen to 18 the paper 
said adding similar declines in profitability were expected for 
natural gas and coal 
